after slice) contains the `limit` newest messages. Then `messages.reverse()` mak
es it ascending order. So `messages[0]` is now the oldest of the returned set, a
nd `messages[messages.length - 1]` is the newest.\n   \n   For cursor pagination
where the next page should get messages older than the current page\'s oldest me
ssage, the cursor should be the `sequence_id` of the oldest message in the curre
nt set, which is `messages[0].sequence_id` after reverse. But wait - the query u
ses `m.sequence_id < :cursor`, meaning cursor is the upper bound (messages must 
